<text>Took my 88 Ford Bronco 2 to Schuck's Transmission a few weeks ago after AAMCO botched a rebuild in 2012. Jeff and his team were very courteous. Jeff took the time to hear me out about the 2-3 shift flare and how I had tried the band adjustment and shift modulator replacement with no improvement before I decided to bring it in for professional repair. Jeff was honest with me about the amount of work it would need. After the repairs, I was able to get a box of the parts that were replaced. While the transmission was being rebuilt, they also replaced the flywheel due to some broken teeth. I inspected their work afterwards and was very pleased to the attention to detail. The shift adjustment nuts on this A4LD are prone to loosening so I saw that Jeff's team had put some gasket on thise after adjustment.

Lesson learned, don't take your transmission to AAMCO for a cheap rebuild. Schuck's has been a good experience and Jeff was willing to take my calls and answer any questions I had. He even provided me with the manuals for the shift kit they installed to improve the shifting after rebuild. I also saw the aftermath of the botched rebuild in the worn bands and worn out center support that was replaced.

I can rest easy now that Schuck's transmission did the job right.</text>< Pictures>

<Rate>1< /Rate>< text>
300% MARKUP on parts used during repair and a THREE WEEK turnaround time? What an embarrassment of a shop. I've waited several months to write this review so that I could evaluate the work done on my automobile. With that said, I highly recommend that you take your automobile elsewhere. It's wise to look outside of the tri-valley area, because the local shops here will rip you off. My classic car was returned to me in an arguably worse condition. It certainly drives a lot worse than when I handed it over to Robert--horrible vibrations. He then had the audacity to justify mark-ups on parts that were ordered from a manufacturer's website (see the attached image). Furthermore, I was never asked which replacement parts I wanted installed on my vehicle. The shop only called me to update the process a single time; I initiated almost all communication during this drawn out process. The total cost was about $500 over-budget (see the attached picture of the poorly written ticket). I don't even think I should make a warranty claim with Schuck's... I'd hate to let my car go for another two months. If you must go to a local shop, go to Broadway motors located on the same block as Schuck's. Do not get scammed here. My friends and I don't call it Schuck's, or truck's, or luck's.... starts with a C!<//text>

< Text>
My garage door began shrieking like a banshee while opening or lowering. I called Precision Door on Friday and got an appointment for Monday morning.
On Monday I got a call from service tech Paul advising me as to his ETA.
He ended up getting held up in a far more extensive job then anticipated with the client before me and my appointment was pushed to the end of the afternoon.
That couldn‚Äôt be helped but I really appreciated the frequent updates Paul provided, his polite and matter-of-fact demeanor and his lack of exaggeration on what time he expected to get to my house.  A person can plan around long delays but not around overly optimistic or unreasonable updates.
Upon arrival the issue was quickly assessed and repaired and 20 minutes later I no longer had a garage door that screamed like a cat in heat.
Price was reasonable but not what I would call rock bottom cheap. Since it wasn‚Äôt something I could do myself it is what it is.  You pay for someone else‚Äôs expertise not just the parts used.
The work he did was clean and expertly performed.
What you need to know is that when you call for an appointment you are calling a call center that, in my case, is not even located in the same state. The scheduler cannot give you any door advise, they simply look for a contractor working for Precision that is in your area.  The definition of ‚Äúin your area‚Äù includes wide swathes of territory and that caller has no clue where you are in relation to where the tech is coming from, hence the very wide service window.  Whoever is going to service the door calls you the day of appointment for a shorter window and updates as they progress.  So I would say the weak link in the chain is the call center since your actual appointment may be far different than what they estimate when you make the first call.  May be earlier or, in my case, may be at the opposite end of the sunrise sunset continuum.  ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è< /Text>

<date>1599273822807<//date><Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
I LOOOOOOVE this place. Birria is one of the foods I always look forward to during the holidays. Anytime I can eat it, I will. How I never imagined putting it in a taco is beyond me. The birria here is tender, juicy, and spot-on saucy. On top of that, the gooey cheese melted on top makes it an irresistible and unctuous combination. Three tacos is quite a large portion. Split it, add a side of elotes, and call it a perfect lunch.< /Text>

On my second visit I unfortunately was scheduled concurrently with a staff meeting, which appeared to simply be a random sales rep dropping by with lunch.  Working in healthcare myself I passed no judgement and decided to maintain my bias internally, however I did inform the receptionist that I still had patients at two separate facilities to work with afterwards.  I was reassured that I would make my timeframe.  I was seated about 45 min after my appointment & then worked on another 45 minutes later. <userid>107346767405260544083<//userid>< user_name>

<date>1386434205825< /date><Rate>1< /Rate>< text>
I'm an AVID researcher.  I conduct loads of research before any purchase. I don't rely solely on Yelp/online reviews because they are so easily skewed.  I should have headed the low star ratings this time.  ;/

Yes, the prices at Simply are good.  The customer service (while IN the store) is great.   The salesmen aren't pushy and awkward.  Jerry was knowledgeable and helped me find EXACTLY what I wanted.   Honest and straight forward.

HOWEVER, if you get a defective product..... You're on your own.   My sectional arrived defective.  A large metal piece hit the ground every time you sat down. I have hard wood floors and it sounded like you were going through the floor!  Less than ideal.  I notified Simply immediately. Like within 12 hours.  It was a holiday weekend so I understood when they didn't call me back.

I called again twice and emailed.  When I finally got someone to speak with me, she informed me because I picked up the couch myself....they wouldn't come get it. I needed to PAY to return it to the manufacturer.   Seriously?    So...they deliver a subpar, "clanky couch" and I had to pay $99 to return it to them.

I was stuck.   It's written in their contract in super fine print.  So....my bad.   I played their game, PAID to have it returned for them to fix.    I needed the couch and didn't want to argue.

Three months later....the same metal piece dangles down.  They fixed nothing.

Yes, I got a great "deal".  For a couch that sounds like your falling to your death upon sitting.

Awesome.

Pay and extra few hundred bucks and go somewhere else.  It's not worth the effort.

I suggest a re-name..... " Simply Hassle Furniture".< /text>

<Name>Ryan McCrobie</Name>< GmapID>
0x80c287b5f8fda5a3:0xad083743a11bfd47<//GmapID>
< Text>
Good selection, the first visit seemed to go very well. As many reviewers have stated - I found good selection and liked the prices. My issue for the most part has been service. I would not tell people not go to this retailer - but I caution the company to strive to do better, because it was rather ridiculous.

I bought a bed for my 3 year old daughter, who of course has a mostly pink and white room. First of all - it came in and no one called me; no follow up as well. I went to pick it up, and it was BLUE - wrong color. The bigger issue was, at first - they COULD NOT FIND my order. I was sitting outside the loading bay for an HOUR.... They found two of the three pieces - so even if it was the right color, I was not going to get out easy.

What I hated the most was that there were probably two really friendly associates - and then a bunch of other people that just made me feel a bit uncomfortable around. It is not a common practice for this group to say hello, offer any form of small talk (which may be fine for some)

When you walk into a store and just stand there waiting awkwardly for anyone to acknowledge you are there - it is just weird. I mean the first rule of retail is environment, and they have a great show room and some good staff - but it doesn't feel like things are connected.

For example - when I went to pick up with bed, I realized I forgot my receipt - so I called them about 10 minutes away to ensure they would have my information and could pick up the bed.

You would think that if a customer calls saying they are 10 minutes away that the product would be waiting for them, or people would be expecting to see you... not the case at all. What the retailer did not know was that it was my wife's 29th birthday and I had to pick her up from a facial after this quick stop - that was nothing close to quick.

Again, order lost - wrong item anyways, poor communication of expectations to the client (me) that was waiting.

The gentleman who helped us out was phenomenal, and the back office seems to do a good job with phone calls and providing service. But in person - everything just feels so much worse. The care you get initially is perfect, but the follow up and the experience that leaves a lasting memory was poor.

I also have to say, it took me a while to actually find the place because they have no signs that say - turn in to this alley for simply discount furniture... so I could see it initially - but had no idea to drive up this little side road to get there.

All and all - many small things that could be done to improve. Again - this is me being constructive because I liked their selection, their prices were very competitive, and initially I felt very positive about the service... it just went downhill from there. Mistakes happen - but there is a better way to go about it. I felt like there was not enough transparency happening and I was just upset that I was not being considered. My time did not feel important when in actually really did matter.

To leave your wife waiting on their Birthday is not a good thing to do - if they were having issues, I would have preferred them to say - we are having issues and cannot get this to you quickly. If you wait an hour to pick up something that YOU KNOW has been there for weeks... then you got a problem. Especially when you leave empty handed.<//Text>

< Text>
One year ago we purchased a 2009 Beaver Monterey Sunset motor home with only 12,600 miles.  In searching for the best option for an extended warranty I found Wholesale Warranties out of San Diego.  My salesman, Steven Motz, kept in touch with me during the time we were negotiating the motor home purchase.  He was fabulous in helping understand their product and options.

After an exhaustive search we purchased from Wholesale Warranties.  Their price was fair and the service after the sale from their claims people has been efficient.  We have experienced a number of claims over the past year including Diesel Engine issues with our CAT C9 engine.

Each claim has been handled on a timely, fair basis.  When this warranty expires at the end of 4 years, my first call will be to Wholesale Warranties for a new extended Warranty.< /Text>

< Rating>

<gmap_id>0x80dc071d8ca7bdf5:0x5b931e6f69a6c05d</gmap_id>< review>
The five stars are for Wholesale Warranties, their company did what they said would, and took care of a repair to our Motor home. We had just recently purchased the motor home used. My complaint was with the RV Repair Shop Double Eagle RV repair on Bolder Hwy in Las Vegas. I saw their add in Sams Town RV Park brochure, so I took our RV there. We talked to a lady at first, in my opinion she seemed to know what she was talking about as I wanted a few things done to our motor home. We went back to the shop to check on the progress and found that she no longer worked there, the guy we talked to seemed to not know what was going on even making a statement that he was just placed into the job and didn't know what was going on, said he needed time to go through the paperwork to get things straight, sounded reasonable to me so we said we would check back in a couple of days, which we did. He didn't know any more then than he knew before, I went over the things I asked to be done with our motor home such as the Generator Serviced including the belt changed, a leak on the roof fixed, mirrors tightened and the Hydraulic Jacks looked at (they were not working right when we purchased it) we also needed the turn signal switch replaced. The total bill they charged was $1721.00. ( it must be noted that Wholesale Warranties with the exception of my $200.00 deductible paid for the replacement of the turn signal)  When we finally went to pick up the motor home I asked what was done and was told the leak on the roof, (they had to replace some caulking around the air horn and antenna)  generator serviced, mirrors tightened, turn signal replaced and the hydraulic jacks were ok. After they brought the motor home out I inspected it and found the mirrors not tightened, where they replaced the caulking on the roof, they used white caulking and I have a black roof you can imagine how that looked, and the hydraulic jacks were doing the same thing they were doing when I took it in. I brought this to their attention and was told to let the them keep it overnight and they would fix this stuff.  So for $1721.00 minus my $200.00 deductible,  I got my Generator Serviced, mirrors finally tightened  and some black paint put on the caulk just where you can see it from the ground, as far as the hydraulic jacks they are still doing the same thing. In my opinion I would stay away from this place.<//review>

Shannon rocked!! She was helpful, knowledgable & friendly. <Rating>5< /Rating><review>Wholesale Warranties and the Viking Protection Plan turned out to be a very beneficial investment.  I usually don't purchase extended service plans, but since we are full time RVers, I figured it would be good insurance in the event of a costly breakdown.  As it turns out, I was correct.

But first, I want to thank Wholesale Warranties, and our Warranty Specialist, Dennis Wacker, for their great service from the purchase of the plan, to filing a claim, to  cancelling the coverage when we traded in our RV.  Dennis was very easy to work with. He clearly explained all aspects of the Viking Protection Plan and walked me through the purchase.  Their rates are very competitive and the plan that I purchased was very comprehensive.

Earlier this year our Norcold frig quit working.  I called a RV refrigerator specialist to come out and take a look.  He determined that we needed a new cooling unit to the tune of $2300.  He contacted the administrator of the Viking Protection Plan to get approval for the repairs.  For whatever reason the repair guy was difficult to deal with and did not want to work with the plan administrator to provide the required information.  In the end, the plan administrator decided to just pay me directly for the repairs and let me deal with the repair guy.  I was very pleased with how the administrator handled the situation.

When we traded in our RV Wholesale Warranties again stepped in and handled the cancellation of the protection plan.  Not only did they plan pay $2200 for the repair of the frig, but we also received the unused prorated premium when we cancelled.

Thank you Wholesale Warranties.< /review><Pics>None</Pics>< response>

<text>I've been to this park in the past and thought it was nice, but this evening I found out just how beautiful Meek Park really is. I wanted to walk and stay close to home so Meek Park it was. < Pictures>
None</Pictures>
< review>
Meek estate park Hayward CA....
Centers around the Meek Mansion/house.
A part of Alameda County..... in the now City of Hayward but known as the "Cherry Land District" in the early 1900's.
Well known for its vast acreage of Cherry and Apricot orchards of that era.

The Meek family were very prominent land owners in the Cherry Land area hence the park name.
Parts of the park/house can be "rented" for Weddings and Gatherings.
The "HARD" park district runs and maintains this park.. and that means a very clean and very well maintained park.
Check out this Piece of Hayward CA History.<//review>
